WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:07.917
♪

00:10.583 --> 00:11.959
JEN: What’s that?

00:11.959 --> 00:14.583
Oh, wow, your
old bedroom junk.

00:14.583 --> 00:15.709
Is your dad finally
turning it

00:15.709 --> 00:17.583
into the tiki bar
he’s always dreamed of?

00:17.583 --> 00:20.375
It was either a tiki bar
or a retro airport lounge

00:20.375 --> 00:21.959
and Mom didn’t want to go
through an X-ray machine

00:21.959 --> 00:23.709
every time
she entered the house.

00:23.709 --> 00:26.166
Trapper Keeper, dude?

00:26.166 --> 00:28.208
Man, remember when
a flap and Velcro

00:28.208 --> 00:30.083
counted as
technology?

00:30.083 --> 00:31.125
(chuckles)

00:31.125 --> 00:32.500
Ooh!

00:32.500 --> 00:34.250
Look what I found.

00:34.250 --> 00:35.834
(gasps)

00:35.834 --> 00:37.291
Wow!

00:37.291 --> 00:40.208
This is money
for my 12th birthday

00:40.208 --> 00:42.333
that I was convinced
Matthew had stolen.

00:42.333 --> 00:45.291
Well, good thing he didn’t,
that’s, like, 200 bucks.

00:45.291 --> 00:48.583
I mean, that could go to,
like, Lark’s college fund.

00:48.583 --> 00:50.250
I got a better idea.

00:50.250 --> 00:52.417
♪

00:52.417 --> 00:54.458
What is that?

00:54.458 --> 00:57.959
This is what I would’ve spent
my 12th birthday money on.

00:57.959 --> 01:00.000
You want to hop in the back,
babe? Go for a ride?

01:00.000 --> 01:00.917
Just kidding, doesn’t work.

01:00.917 --> 01:01.834
(clears throat)

01:01.834 --> 01:03.959
But do not worry.

01:03.959 --> 01:06.625
Because I’m gonna
restore it.

01:06.625 --> 01:09.000
Why does it smell like
gas if it doesn’t run?

01:09.000 --> 01:11.834
Ah, the previous owner
was trying to burn it.

01:11.834 --> 01:13.709
So, yeah.

01:13.709 --> 01:15.000
Don’t smoke around it.

01:15.000 --> 01:15.917
♪

01:15.917 --> 01:18.417
JOHN: Well, my tiki bar’s
almost ready.

01:18.417 --> 01:19.500
Next brunch,
we’re gonna have

01:19.500 --> 01:21.458
a steel drum
playing in the corner.

01:21.458 --> 01:24.208
John, I said no
to the steel drum.

01:24.208 --> 01:25.917
Well, then, we’re gonna
have a Rastafarian

01:25.917 --> 01:28.083
in the corner doing nothing.

01:28.083 --> 01:30.375
GREG: Oh, hey, by the way,
Matt, you’ll like this.

01:30.375 --> 01:32.625
I found my 12th
birthday money

01:32.625 --> 01:35.041
in an old Trapper Keeper.

01:35.041 --> 01:36.125
You what?

01:36.125 --> 01:37.041
HEATHER: Wait a minute,
wait a minute,

01:37.041 --> 01:38.417
I thought that Matt
took that money.

01:38.417 --> 01:39.458
Yeah, you know, I did too.

01:39.458 --> 01:40.959
But it turns out
I’ve had it this whole time.

01:40.959 --> 01:42.125
(laughs)

01:42.125 --> 01:43.583
So I used the money
to buy the dirt bike

01:43.583 --> 01:44.500
that I’ve always wanted.

01:44.500 --> 01:45.917
You know,
so it all worked out.

01:45.917 --> 01:47.750
Oh, it all worked out?

01:47.750 --> 01:50.709
Do you know how long
I was grounded for that?

01:50.709 --> 01:53.333
JOHN: Not long enough
to learn your lesson.

01:53.333 --> 01:54.542
He just said
I didn’t do it.

01:54.542 --> 01:56.291
I didn’t see evidence
of that.

01:56.291 --> 01:58.583
’Cause he spent it
on a dirt bike.

01:58.583 --> 02:00.583
Greg, just apologize
to your brother.

02:00.583 --> 02:02.208
You know his
anger issues.

02:02.208 --> 02:03.834
I never had
any anger issues

02:03.834 --> 02:05.250
until I was
wrongly accused.

02:05.250 --> 02:06.542
Whoa, okay, Matt.

02:06.542 --> 02:07.709
I am sorry.

02:07.709 --> 02:08.625
Geez, wow.

02:08.625 --> 02:10.875
I didn’t think
you’d be so upset.

02:10.875 --> 02:12.041
Beautiful apology.

02:12.041 --> 02:13.709
Way to take
the high road, kid.

02:13.709 --> 02:17.333
Oh--do you know
that my entire reputation

02:17.333 --> 02:19.083
in this family
changed on that day?

02:19.083 --> 02:20.166
Suddenly, we were
the good son,

02:20.166 --> 02:21.250
the bad son,
and the slut.

02:21.250 --> 02:22.792
-Mm.
-Really, Heather?

02:22.792 --> 02:23.709
Oh, come on, babe.

02:23.709 --> 02:24.917
We had sex in your car
on our first date.

02:24.917 --> 02:26.041
You can’t be
that surprised.

02:26.041 --> 02:27.333
Oh, for God’s sake.

02:27.333 --> 02:29.583
Look, I was
a stupid little kid,

02:29.583 --> 02:31.000
and I apologize.

02:31.000 --> 02:32.750
What more do you want?

02:32.750 --> 02:34.667
-You can give me the bike.
-What?

02:34.667 --> 02:36.834
So I can smash it like
you smashed my reputation.

02:36.834 --> 02:37.792
Oh, no way.

02:37.792 --> 02:38.709
I am restoring it.

02:38.709 --> 02:39.667
MATT: You know what
you can’t restore?

02:39.667 --> 02:40.875
You can’t restore
my childhood.

02:40.875 --> 02:42.458
MATT: Greg, give me the bike.
GREG: No.

02:42.458 --> 02:44.750
Imagine how much nicer
this fight would be

02:44.750 --> 02:46.000
with steel drums playing.

02:46.000 --> 02:47.959
No.

02:47.959 --> 02:49.792
GREG: Pretty romantic
dinner we’re having.

02:49.792 --> 02:52.750
Just you and me and no
Lark in a baby seat.

02:52.750 --> 02:56.417
JEN: Yeah, if only I could
get you out of your baby seat.

02:56.417 --> 02:57.709
Nuh-uh.
No way.

02:57.709 --> 03:00.208
No way I’m letting
this out of my sight,

03:00.208 --> 03:01.917
now that I know
that Matt wants it.

03:01.917 --> 03:03.583
Just give it to him, Greg.

03:03.583 --> 03:05.667
I mean, I don’t want this
to come out the wrong way,

03:05.667 --> 03:08.333
but Matt,
he’s got nothing.

03:08.333 --> 03:10.125
You know, I mean, sure,
he’s got Colleen,

03:10.125 --> 03:12.542
but who knows
for how long.

03:12.542 --> 03:13.458
Whoa, you don’t think
that they’re--

03:13.458 --> 03:14.834
Point is,
if trashing this bike

03:14.834 --> 03:16.583
is gonna get your brother
to move past this,

03:16.583 --> 03:17.667
isn’t that worth it?

03:18.792 --> 03:19.709
No.

03:19.709 --> 03:22.000
I mean, especially if I can
find a little mini sidecar

03:22.000 --> 03:24.750
for this thing, I’m gonna be
the coolest dad on the block.

03:24.750 --> 03:27.291
♪

03:27.291 --> 03:28.250
(Greg exhales)

03:30.625 --> 03:31.834
No.

03:39.667 --> 03:41.583
It’s like he’s hurt.

03:41.583 --> 03:43.709
Like he wants me
to follow him.

03:43.709 --> 03:48.417
♪

03:48.417 --> 03:50.500
Be careful, that’s vintage.

03:50.500 --> 03:51.667
(door closes)

03:55.583 --> 03:56.834
Dude, what the hell
was that for?

03:56.834 --> 03:58.458
GREG: You know exactly
what that was for.

03:58.458 --> 04:00.125
Now you’ve angered
the tiki gods.

04:00.125 --> 04:02.750
This year’s banana crop
is gonna suck.

04:02.750 --> 04:04.375
Good job, Matt.
Look what you did.

04:04.375 --> 04:06.583
What are you talking about?
You’re the one who pushed me.

04:07.917 --> 04:09.917
JOAN: Hey, hey!

04:09.917 --> 04:11.500
What’s going on in here?

04:11.500 --> 04:13.875
Greg pushed me
and broke the tiki god.

04:13.875 --> 04:15.250
Is that true, Greg?

04:15.250 --> 04:17.291
Yeah, but only because
Matthew stole my dirt bike.

04:17.291 --> 04:18.917
-Wha...?
JOAN: Is that true, Matt?

04:18.917 --> 04:20.625
Did you steal his dirt bike?

04:20.625 --> 04:22.041
What?
Of course not.

04:22.041 --> 04:24.041
You said, in front
of everyone,

04:24.041 --> 04:25.208
that you wanted
to smash it.

04:25.208 --> 04:26.250
We all heard you, Matt.

04:26.250 --> 04:27.750
How can you be so petty?

04:27.750 --> 04:29.417
But I didn’t do anything,
I swear.

04:29.417 --> 04:31.041
It’s like my 12th birthday
all over again.

04:31.041 --> 04:32.125
Yeah, but I didn’t
take your money,

04:32.125 --> 04:33.834
you said so yourself.

04:33.834 --> 04:36.083
Well, maybe now
I’m not so sure.

04:36.083 --> 04:38.667
Maybe you hid it from
me this whole time.

04:38.667 --> 04:40.000
Did you do that, Matt?

04:40.000 --> 04:41.375
JOAN: Did you hide his money

04:41.375 --> 04:43.041
in the back
of his Trapper Keeper

04:43.041 --> 04:45.083
so he wouldn’t be able
to find it?

04:45.083 --> 04:47.500
Did you?

04:47.500 --> 04:48.917
Excuse me.

04:48.917 --> 04:51.709
I’m gonna go in search
of my birth family.

04:51.709 --> 04:54.709
♪

04:54.709 --> 04:56.333
You gonna steal
from them, too?

04:56.333 --> 04:59.250
♪

05:03.041 --> 05:04.834
Hey.

05:04.834 --> 05:05.834
What are you doing?

05:05.834 --> 05:07.458
Oh, you know,
just cleaning up

05:07.458 --> 05:09.333
my dirt bike oil
with my tears.

05:09.333 --> 05:12.417
JEN: Oh, yeah, that got all
over the inside of my car, too.

05:14.333 --> 05:15.875
Wait, why was it in your car?

05:15.875 --> 05:18.166
Oh, well, I’m getting it
restored for you.

05:18.166 --> 05:19.917
I didn’t know what to get you
for your birthday next month,

05:19.917 --> 05:21.959
and I just figured it
was better than socks.

05:21.959 --> 05:23.375
Oh, this is terrible.

05:23.375 --> 05:24.291
Well, I can still
get you the socks.

05:24.291 --> 05:25.667
I just, I hate
spending money on them

05:25.667 --> 05:26.625
when you won’t clip
your toenails.

05:26.625 --> 05:29.083
No, no, no,
I just accused Matthew

05:29.083 --> 05:30.000
of stealing it.

05:30.000 --> 05:32.208
No, again?

05:32.208 --> 05:34.166
Well, you have to go
apologize to him now.

05:35.959 --> 05:38.458
Or you and I can move
far, far away from here

05:38.458 --> 05:40.834
and never see
my family again.

05:40.834 --> 05:41.834
I have a go bag
in the garage,

05:41.834 --> 05:43.041
we can be out of here
in 20 minutes.

05:43.041 --> 05:44.125
Okay.

05:44.125 --> 05:46.041
♪

05:46.041 --> 05:48.125
Wait, a go bag?

05:48.125 --> 05:50.083
Let’s go, let’s go!

05:50.083 --> 05:50.959
Huh.

05:51.583 --> 05:55.625
♪

05:55.625 --> 05:57.458
John?

05:57.458 --> 05:59.500
I can’t find my wedding ring.

05:59.500 --> 06:01.166
I’ve turned the whole house
upside down.

06:01.166 --> 06:03.250
Oh, your ring’s right here.

06:03.250 --> 06:05.041
-Oh!
JOHN: Mm-hmm.

06:05.041 --> 06:06.667
Heather brought it over.

06:06.667 --> 06:09.000
Oh! I must’ve
over-lotioned.

06:09.000 --> 06:11.333
My jewelry’s been
falling off all day.

06:11.333 --> 06:12.417
No, no, you baked it

06:12.417 --> 06:14.792
into the banana bread
that you gave them.

06:14.792 --> 06:16.250
Oh, dear.

06:18.166 --> 06:20.667
This didn’t go through Tim,
did it?

06:20.667 --> 06:22.959
All I know is she didn’t
want to embarrass you.

06:22.959 --> 06:24.959
Why would
that embarrass me?

06:24.959 --> 06:27.750
Uh, because Heather
said you were getting old,

06:27.750 --> 06:30.542
uh, and also, um...

06:30.542 --> 06:32.458
uh, it did go
through Tim.

06:32.458 --> 06:38.917
♪

06:38.917 --> 06:41.959
JOAN: There’s my
future Olympian!

06:41.959 --> 06:44.625
I don’t want to be
in the Olympics, Mom-Mom.

06:44.625 --> 06:47.458
I want to be ready for
the zombie apocalypse.

06:47.458 --> 06:48.375
Fun.

06:48.375 --> 06:50.000
You won’t say "fun"
when you have to choose

06:50.000 --> 06:52.208
between family
and survival.

06:52.208 --> 06:53.583
Oh, well.

06:53.583 --> 06:54.959
Let’s hit the road.

06:54.959 --> 06:57.375
Hey, Mom, why don’t you
let me drive her today?

06:57.375 --> 06:59.417
You know, it’s dark
when her class gets out,

06:59.417 --> 07:01.291
and it’s hard to see
that off-ramp.

07:01.291 --> 07:02.291
Why don’t you get
going, sweetie?

07:02.291 --> 07:03.125
We’re gonna be late.

07:04.208 --> 07:06.583
Oh, I get it.

07:06.583 --> 07:08.917
I’ll just stay home,
and I’ll separate my pills

07:08.917 --> 07:11.375
for every day of the week.

07:11.375 --> 07:13.250
It’s good to keep busy.

07:13.250 --> 07:14.208
All right, let’s go.

07:14.208 --> 07:15.917
Bye, Mom, love you.

07:17.667 --> 07:18.625
Hmm.

07:18.625 --> 07:19.709
♪

07:19.709 --> 07:23.125
JOHN: Five, six, seven.

07:23.125 --> 07:26.125
JOAN: She thinks I’m old
because I’m 68.

07:26.125 --> 07:28.583
69, 70...

07:28.583 --> 07:30.834
Oh, Joanie,
damn it.

07:30.834 --> 07:32.792
Now you made me
lose count.

07:32.792 --> 07:34.917
Now it’s all guesswork
till Monday.

07:34.917 --> 07:36.959
Do you think
I’m old, John?

07:36.959 --> 07:39.208
Well, you’re not new,

07:39.208 --> 07:41.208
except for your hips
and your knee.

07:41.208 --> 07:42.667
JOAN: No, I’m making mistakes

07:42.667 --> 07:44.458
that any normal person
would make,

07:44.458 --> 07:45.458
but because
of my age,

07:45.458 --> 07:47.917
she’s suddenly writing
me off like I’m old.

07:47.917 --> 07:49.709
Isn’t that how
you treated your mother?

07:49.709 --> 07:50.917
She was old.

07:50.917 --> 07:54.083
So, talk to Heather
about it.

07:54.083 --> 07:57.083
You know zip about
mother/daughter relationships.

07:57.083 --> 07:58.917
It’s not about talking.

07:58.917 --> 08:03.333
It’s about teaching a lesson
through total humiliation.

08:03.333 --> 08:05.208
♪

08:05.208 --> 08:07.125
HEATHER: Mom, honestly,
I could have driven.

08:07.125 --> 08:08.875
JOAN: Nonsense,
it’s still daylight,

08:08.875 --> 08:11.500
so all the blurry objects
are still quite bright.

08:11.500 --> 08:13.041
(Heather chuckles nervously)

08:13.041 --> 08:14.542
How am I on your side, dear?

08:14.542 --> 08:15.875
HEATHER: I think we’re good.

08:15.875 --> 08:17.083
Yep.

08:17.083 --> 08:21.583
♪

08:21.583 --> 08:24.166
I hope they have
a purple sweat suit

08:24.166 --> 08:26.500
that doesn’t show
the stains.

08:26.500 --> 08:27.667
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.

08:27.667 --> 08:29.792
I don’t know about that, Mom,
but what about this?

08:29.792 --> 08:31.208
In your size.
Cute, right?

08:31.208 --> 08:33.458
It’s a little showy.

08:33.458 --> 08:36.834
Do they have anything
with cats on it?

08:36.834 --> 08:38.917
SOPHIA: Now you’re talking,
Mom-Mom.

08:38.917 --> 08:40.583
Very loudly, by the way.

08:40.583 --> 08:44.166
Oh, thank you, dear.

08:47.625 --> 08:49.166
Mom-Mom, what
are you doing?

08:49.166 --> 08:50.625
It’s okay, it’s okay.

08:54.166 --> 08:55.417
Mom, you look great.

08:55.417 --> 08:58.417
Let’s go buy that, and you
don’t have to take it off.

08:58.417 --> 09:00.083
-Hold on.
HEATHER: Yeah.

09:00.083 --> 09:01.667
I want to try on these pants.

09:03.208 --> 09:04.750
Do you think this is
like the shoe store

09:04.750 --> 09:06.583
where you have to be
wearing a sock?

09:06.583 --> 09:10.125
♪

09:10.125 --> 09:13.083
I’m like a kid
in a candy shop.

09:13.083 --> 09:14.542
(chuckles nervously)

09:16.083 --> 09:19.500
Ugh.

09:19.500 --> 09:20.875
-She did it again.
-I know, I know,

09:20.875 --> 09:22.458
just leave Mom-Mom
alone, okay?

09:22.458 --> 09:24.417
-What was that, Heather?
HEATHER: Oh, I was just saying

09:24.417 --> 09:25.959
maybe you want
some hard candies.

09:25.959 --> 09:28.917
Oh, I already have some.

09:28.917 --> 09:30.625
Mom, did you pay for those?

09:30.625 --> 09:32.458
JOAN: Look, a Chico’s.

09:32.458 --> 09:33.375
HEATHER: I am so sorry.

09:33.375 --> 09:34.458
Come on, honey,
follow her, follow her,

09:34.458 --> 09:35.792
go, go, go, go, go.

09:35.792 --> 09:37.166
♪

09:37.166 --> 09:38.959
-Mom?
-Mom-Mom.

09:40.500 --> 09:42.417
God, where the hell is she?

09:42.417 --> 09:44.667
This just happened
so quickly.

09:44.667 --> 09:47.750
I thought you could
only lose little kids.

09:47.750 --> 09:50.083
Well, at a
certain point,

09:50.083 --> 09:51.750
adults become like
little kids again.

09:51.750 --> 09:53.250
(train whistle blows)

09:53.250 --> 09:54.750
Do you mean like that?

09:54.750 --> 09:55.667
(train whistle blows)

09:55.667 --> 09:58.208
JOAN: All aboard!

09:58.208 --> 10:00.041
Next stop, Zales!

10:00.041 --> 10:02.417
Ma’am, you need to take
a three-hour course

10:02.417 --> 10:04.583
to operate
the mall choo-choo!

10:08.917 --> 10:10.208
HEATHER: Mom.

10:10.208 --> 10:11.125
Mom, what are you doing?

10:11.125 --> 10:13.834
You can’t steal
the mall train.

10:13.834 --> 10:17.000
I’m just being the crazy old
lady you think I am.

10:17.000 --> 10:17.917
What are you
talking about?

10:17.917 --> 10:20.208
I don’t think you’re
a crazy old lady.

10:20.208 --> 10:22.000
I’ve been acting
senile all day

10:22.000 --> 10:23.041
and you haven’t
said a word.

10:23.041 --> 10:25.208
You just kept
letting it slide.

10:25.208 --> 10:26.834
I thought I could
count on you.

10:26.834 --> 10:28.917
Mom, you can count on me.

10:28.917 --> 10:31.583
I was trying to protect
your feelings.

10:31.583 --> 10:34.458
Never, ever treat me
like an old lady,

10:34.458 --> 10:37.959
because the moment you do,
that’s when I become one,

10:37.959 --> 10:40.333
and I’m a long way from that.

10:42.250 --> 10:46.500
-You got it?
HEATHER: Yeah, I got it.

10:46.500 --> 10:47.875
SECURITY: Ma’am?

10:47.875 --> 10:49.709
I need you to wait here
until the police arrive.

10:52.166 --> 10:53.583
Billy?

10:53.583 --> 10:55.709
Is it you?

10:55.709 --> 10:57.291
Billy, is the war over?

10:57.291 --> 10:59.125
Oh, Billy, you’re home.

10:59.125 --> 11:02.250
Oh, no, she has
really lost it.

11:02.250 --> 11:03.625
Oh, Mom, Mom.

11:03.625 --> 11:06.959
Come on, we’re gonna go back
to the lollipop castle.

11:06.959 --> 11:08.750
That’s what we call
the home.

11:08.750 --> 11:09.834
Thank you.

11:09.834 --> 11:10.875
Okay, let’s go.

11:10.875 --> 11:15.542
♪

11:15.542 --> 11:18.709
COLLEEN: It’s a very distinct
loud, buzzy-rattly sound,

11:18.709 --> 11:21.625
like, um, like a rattlesnake
on a game show.

11:21.625 --> 11:23.709
You know what, I bet they
already have that in Japan.

11:26.291 --> 11:29.500
♪

11:31.166 --> 11:33.458
I’m sorry, but your car’s
not making the noise.

11:33.458 --> 11:36.250
You mean you couldn’t find
the source of the noise.

11:36.250 --> 11:38.250
No, there’s no noise.

11:38.250 --> 11:41.375
And I can’t fix something
if I can’t find it.

11:41.375 --> 11:43.917
COLLEEN: So, you’re just
not gonna fix my car?

11:43.917 --> 11:45.834
DABNEY: We only fix cars
that are broken here.

11:45.834 --> 11:48.375
Well, that’s quite a policy.

11:49.375 --> 11:51.417
Thank you for your help.

11:51.417 --> 11:54.750
♪

11:54.750 --> 11:56.125
(buzzy-rattly noise starts)

11:56.125 --> 11:57.709
You’re kidding me!

11:57.709 --> 12:00.166
Come on!

12:00.166 --> 12:01.792
Where are you at?

12:01.792 --> 12:02.750
♪

12:02.750 --> 12:04.625
The point is
this auto mechanic

12:04.625 --> 12:06.291
didn’t think I knew
what I was talking about

12:06.291 --> 12:08.083
because I’m a woman,

12:08.083 --> 12:09.291
which made me feel
really terrible

12:09.291 --> 12:11.041
because I didn’t know
what I was talking about.

12:11.041 --> 12:12.458
Yeah, you see,
you can’t let this guy

12:12.458 --> 12:13.917
get away with
treating you this way.

12:13.917 --> 12:16.959
You need to retaliate
in the place that matters most.

12:18.417 --> 12:19.834
Go after his kids?

12:19.834 --> 12:21.000
JEN: Wow.

12:21.000 --> 12:22.375
No, didn’t see that one coming.

12:22.375 --> 12:23.458
Yeah, that went dark fast.

12:23.458 --> 12:25.250
No, I was thinking just
going online and, like,

12:25.250 --> 12:26.208
ripping him a new one.

12:26.208 --> 12:27.583
Oh. I like that.

12:27.583 --> 12:28.500
-Yeah.
COLLEEN: Okay.

12:28.500 --> 12:31.083
"Jeser and Sons Auto Repair,
rate your experience."

12:31.083 --> 12:32.291
(clears throat)

12:32.291 --> 12:33.792
One star.

12:33.792 --> 12:36.834
"My mechanic, Dabney,
was rude and unhelpful."

12:36.834 --> 12:38.417
Ooh! I’ve got shivers.

12:38.417 --> 12:39.709
It’s so real now.

12:39.709 --> 12:40.625
Oh.

12:40.625 --> 12:41.834
Well, one star
could get him fired,

12:41.834 --> 12:43.667
and I don’t want
to ruin his career.

12:43.667 --> 12:45.458
I just want to
teach him a lesson.

12:45.458 --> 12:47.667
-Two stars.
JEN: Well, that’s still bad.

12:47.667 --> 12:49.542
Of course, I don’t know what
kind of day he was having.

12:49.542 --> 12:51.291
And he...
he was honest,

12:51.291 --> 12:53.375
which takes
a lot of courage.

12:53.375 --> 12:54.834
Three stars.

12:54.834 --> 12:57.458
Well, there’s power
in kindness, too, but...

12:57.458 --> 12:58.375
COLLEEN: Who am I to judge?

12:58.375 --> 12:59.500
I don’t know anything
about cars.

12:59.500 --> 13:00.875
He even saved me money.

13:00.875 --> 13:02.083
Four stars.

13:02.083 --> 13:03.375
And you know,
in this day and age,

13:03.375 --> 13:04.667
people are so focused
on the negative,

13:04.667 --> 13:06.375
I want to be part
of the solution.

13:06.375 --> 13:08.458
Five stars.

13:08.458 --> 13:09.709
"Dabney couldn’t help me,

13:09.709 --> 13:11.792
but I am sure
he can help you."

13:11.792 --> 13:12.709
(exhales loudly)

13:12.709 --> 13:13.875
That feels good.

13:13.875 --> 13:15.625
Thank you so much, Jen.

13:15.625 --> 13:18.792
JEN: You know, if you really
want to teach this guy a lesson,

13:18.792 --> 13:21.333
send him a nice gift basket.

13:21.333 --> 13:22.792
Do you think that would work?

13:22.792 --> 13:23.917
No.

13:23.917 --> 13:26.291
♪

13:26.291 --> 13:28.834
-I don’t hear it.
-Shh!

13:28.834 --> 13:30.875
Ugh, it’s like the car knows
there’s a man in here

13:30.875 --> 13:31.959
and wants me to look dumb.

13:31.959 --> 13:33.750
Okay, well let’s not
float that theory

13:33.750 --> 13:34.709
in front
of the mechanic.

13:34.709 --> 13:36.417
You don’t get it, Matt.

13:36.417 --> 13:38.083
You’re a straight,
white male.

13:38.083 --> 13:40.542
No one has ever talked to you
like you’re dumb.

13:40.542 --> 13:42.667
Except for you,
right now.

13:42.667 --> 13:44.542
♪

13:44.542 --> 13:47.083
My fiancé thought that you’d
take me more seriously

13:47.083 --> 13:49.166
if I had a man by my side.

13:49.166 --> 13:51.417
But I say,
hell no.

13:51.417 --> 13:53.417
I have something
just as good as a man.

13:53.417 --> 13:56.000
I have three women.

13:56.000 --> 13:57.917
Do they have
car problems, too?

13:57.917 --> 13:59.667
COLLEEN: Well, not today.

13:59.667 --> 14:01.000
But maybe someday.

14:01.000 --> 14:02.667
And where are they
gonna spend their money?

14:02.667 --> 14:03.583
Here?

14:03.583 --> 14:05.500
Where they’re treated
like fools?

14:05.500 --> 14:08.959
Or at a garage where all humans
are treated as equal?

14:08.959 --> 14:10.542
Endowed by their creator
with certain

14:10.542 --> 14:12.625
"inalnable..."
"unanaba...

14:12.625 --> 14:13.792
JEN: Inalienable rights.

14:13.792 --> 14:15.667
She did it right
on the way over.

14:15.667 --> 14:18.125
COLLEEN: Maybe you
don’t hear that noise,

14:18.125 --> 14:19.625
but I hear it.

14:19.625 --> 14:20.875
And I hear it.

14:20.875 --> 14:22.041
And I hear it.

14:22.041 --> 14:23.083
And I hear it.

14:23.083 --> 14:24.250
ACTIVIST: Can we
speed this along?

14:24.250 --> 14:26.959
I’m a very busy
women’s rights activist.

14:26.959 --> 14:29.041
COLLEEN: I’m so sorry,
I’m almost done.

14:29.041 --> 14:30.458
That sound
you don’t hear...

14:30.458 --> 14:32.208
Okay, okay.

14:32.208 --> 14:34.000
I’m happy to take
another look.

14:35.458 --> 14:36.750
Thank you.

14:38.166 --> 14:39.333
-Yes!
JOAN: Oh, gosh,

14:39.333 --> 14:42.417
I have to release some
of that negative body language.

14:42.417 --> 14:43.500
JEN: Oh.

14:43.500 --> 14:44.417
♪

14:44.417 --> 14:46.375
JOAN: Ah-ee!

14:46.375 --> 14:48.208
Moving in a circle
really does make me

14:48.208 --> 14:50.375
feel my feminine power.

14:50.375 --> 14:52.500
DABNEY: Okay.

14:52.500 --> 14:53.625
You were right.

14:53.625 --> 14:54.750
There was a sound.

14:54.750 --> 14:57.208
-I knew it!
-Good for you, dear!

14:57.208 --> 14:58.208
Well, what was it?

14:58.208 --> 14:59.834
Oh, don’t even worry about it,
I just took care of it.

14:59.834 --> 15:01.959
-No charge.
COLLEEN: No, tell me.

15:01.959 --> 15:05.041
Or, what? Does the little lady
not know what engine names are?

15:06.667 --> 15:08.959
Well, I was trying
to be sensitive, but, uh,

15:08.959 --> 15:10.917
trapped in between
your seat and the console...

15:10.917 --> 15:13.208
COLLEEN: Uh-huh?
-...was, uh,

15:13.208 --> 15:14.792
this personal massager.

15:14.792 --> 15:16.959
(buzzing)

15:18.792 --> 15:19.834
(clears throat, buzzing stops)

15:19.834 --> 15:21.417
I used to have
a longer commute.

15:22.083 --> 15:26.041
♪

15:26.041 --> 15:27.875
SOPHIA: We don’t need
to steal a bus.

15:27.875 --> 15:29.542
We’ve got talent.

15:29.542 --> 15:31.166
We’re like
the von Trapp family,

15:31.166 --> 15:33.375
except the French aren’t
trying to kill us.

15:33.375 --> 15:36.542
-Did you even watch that movie?
-No.

15:39.333 --> 15:43.542
♪

15:43.542 --> 15:45.542
TIM: Whoa!
You guys feel that?

15:45.542 --> 15:47.000
It’s an earthquake!

15:48.125 --> 15:49.083
Drill!

15:49.083 --> 15:51.125
(kids groan)

15:51.125 --> 15:53.834
SOPHIA: You said we were going
to Chinatown for dumplings.

15:53.834 --> 15:56.041
TYLER: Yeah, and Triple Dragon
has the best dumps in town.

15:56.041 --> 15:58.542
SAMANTHA: I know you think
that shortening words is cool,

15:58.542 --> 16:00.000
-but it’s not.
TYLER: That’s exactly why

16:00.000 --> 16:02.500
-you don’t have a boyf.
TIM: All right, no dumplings.

16:02.500 --> 16:04.125
When a 6.9
earthquake hits,

16:04.125 --> 16:05.417
the Hugheses
will be ready,

16:05.417 --> 16:08.500
and since you all "died"
in my tsunami drill,

16:08.500 --> 16:09.750
this is your big chance
at redemption.

16:09.750 --> 16:11.375
Everyone died
in your tsunami drill.

16:11.375 --> 16:13.583
Yeah, well,
it was a tsunami.

16:13.583 --> 16:16.166
Now hand over your wallets
and your phones and get out.

16:16.166 --> 16:17.458
Mom was on board with this?

16:17.458 --> 16:19.250
Eh, your mother got
to pick the last movie,

16:19.250 --> 16:20.625
so I get this.

16:20.625 --> 16:22.834
Come on, out,
out you go.

16:22.834 --> 16:24.125
You all need
to make it home

16:24.125 --> 16:26.583
relying only on each other
and your wits to survive.

16:26.583 --> 16:30.041
And I pray that at least two
of you make it home alive.

16:30.041 --> 16:31.542
And I hope one
of that one of those two

16:31.542 --> 16:33.000
is Sophia.

16:33.000 --> 16:34.166
Good luck!

16:34.166 --> 16:35.458
Aftershock!

16:35.458 --> 16:37.542
Agh!

16:37.542 --> 16:39.291
(Tim laughs)

16:39.291 --> 16:40.208
TYLER: Okay.

16:40.208 --> 16:44.542
♪

16:44.542 --> 16:46.333
I guess he’s really
not coming back.

16:46.333 --> 16:48.583
What a strange
parenting decision.

16:48.583 --> 16:50.083
What do we do now?

16:50.083 --> 16:52.500
I know, we can steal a car.

16:52.500 --> 16:54.500
I say we call Clem
to come get us.

16:54.500 --> 16:56.709
See, guys? No downside
to getting married early.

16:56.709 --> 17:00.166
If you guys had husbands,
we’d call them, but you don’t.

17:00.166 --> 17:02.375
-Uh, excuse me...
-No, that’s cheating.

17:02.375 --> 17:03.709
That guy’s useless,

17:03.709 --> 17:05.375
unless we’re
gonna eat him.

17:05.375 --> 17:06.542
SAMANTHA: I saw it online.

17:06.542 --> 17:07.625
You remove the plastic cover

17:07.625 --> 17:09.917
from the steering column,
find the wiring harness...

17:09.917 --> 17:11.583
TYLER: We are not
stealing a car.

17:11.583 --> 17:13.041
Well, I can’t jack one
without a gun.

17:13.041 --> 17:14.208
SOPHIA: How about
we use that thing

17:14.208 --> 17:17.583
my gym teacher uses to call
the woman who isn’t his wife?

17:19.792 --> 17:21.917
♪

17:24.208 --> 17:26.625
You guys don’t happen to
know Clem’s number, do you?

17:26.625 --> 17:28.417
You don’t know your
own wife’s phone number?

17:28.417 --> 17:29.375
Why would I need
to know it?

17:29.375 --> 17:30.458
She’s in my contacts.

17:30.458 --> 17:33.250
And who uses a real phone
other than prisoners?

17:33.250 --> 17:35.875
I’m sure Mom-Mom
will come pick us up.

17:35.875 --> 17:38.625
What’s Mom-Mom’s
phone number?

17:38.625 --> 17:41.333
Do any of us know
anyone’s phone number?

17:41.333 --> 17:42.792
SOPHIA: I know 911.

17:42.792 --> 17:45.125
We could report Dad
for child abuse.

17:45.125 --> 17:46.125
No...

17:47.291 --> 17:48.834
One, two, three, four.

17:48.834 --> 17:51.458
ALL:<i> ♪ Children</i>
<i>of the quake, yeah ♪</i>

17:51.458 --> 17:54.041
<i>♪ Children of the quake, yeah ♪</i>

17:54.041 --> 17:58.000
<i>-♪ Livin’ on a fault ♪</i>
ALL:<i> ♪ With no one to blame ♪</i>

17:58.000 --> 17:59.041
PASSERBY: They seem
kind of well-off

17:59.041 --> 18:00.583
to be begging for money,
don’t you think?

18:00.583 --> 18:01.917
PASSERBY: Little one’s
got highlights.

18:04.625 --> 18:06.000
-What do we got?
-Just a picture

18:06.000 --> 18:09.542
of a mushroom with two
walnuts at the bottom.

18:09.542 --> 18:10.750
Oh.

18:10.750 --> 18:12.041
No.

18:14.792 --> 18:18.333
♪

18:18.333 --> 18:19.959
TYLER: Where did you get that?

18:19.959 --> 18:22.792
The guy under the overpass
sold it to me for a dollar.

18:22.792 --> 18:24.417
You had a dollar?

18:24.417 --> 18:26.792
Yeah, I always keep
a dollar in my shoe.

18:26.792 --> 18:28.625
To support my candy habit.

18:28.625 --> 18:31.375
WOMAN: You kids are adorable.

18:31.375 --> 18:33.000
Thank you.

18:33.000 --> 18:34.625
Oh, thank you so much.

18:34.625 --> 18:36.500
That’s really
gonna help us out.

18:37.583 --> 18:39.333
Oops.

18:39.333 --> 18:40.458
Come and get it.

18:41.959 --> 18:44.834
Looks like your drapes
match my curtains.

18:47.500 --> 18:52.166
♪

18:52.166 --> 18:53.583
TYLER: I didn’t like that.

18:53.583 --> 18:56.000
Nothing I touched
felt the way I expected.

18:56.000 --> 18:57.083
I can’t believe
we had to grab

18:57.083 --> 18:58.792
your other arm
to pull you out.

18:58.792 --> 19:02.417
Here, Dad gave me
some hand sanitizer.

19:06.083 --> 19:08.125
Sophia!

19:08.125 --> 19:09.792
-And a phone.
SAMANTHA: You had that phone

19:09.792 --> 19:12.458
-the whole time?
SOPHIA: Yeah.

19:12.458 --> 19:14.625
Dad said to use it
in case of an emergency,

19:14.625 --> 19:16.834
like if there’s
a real earthquake.

19:16.834 --> 19:18.792
But I didn’t want to.

19:18.792 --> 19:20.834
SAMANTHA: Well, I didn’t want to
watch Tyler cheat on Clementine

19:20.834 --> 19:22.375
with that other woman,
but I did.

19:22.375 --> 19:24.792
Don’t you say that.
Don’t you dare say that.

19:24.792 --> 19:27.542
I’m sorry, it’s just
that the three of us

19:27.542 --> 19:29.583
never hang out anymore.

19:29.583 --> 19:30.709
I mean, Sam,

19:30.709 --> 19:32.834
you have your acting,
and boxing,

19:32.834 --> 19:34.417
and school,
and friends.

19:34.417 --> 19:36.583
And, Tyler,
you’re married,

19:36.583 --> 19:39.041
and...
that’s...

19:39.041 --> 19:40.000
well, that’s it.

19:40.000 --> 19:43.542
But today was just like
old times, you know?

19:43.542 --> 19:44.834
When we were kids.

19:48.542 --> 19:50.917
You know, maybe this drill
doesn’t have to end quite yet.

19:52.834 --> 19:54.834
(kids laughing)

19:54.834 --> 19:56.375
These are so good.

19:56.375 --> 19:57.917
I know, they almost
make me forget

19:57.917 --> 20:00.041
I felt up an old lady.

20:00.041 --> 20:01.208
Nope, there it is.

20:01.208 --> 20:02.709
(Samantha laughs)

20:02.709 --> 20:05.125
(phone ringing)

20:06.000 --> 20:07.208
It’s Dad.

20:08.625 --> 20:09.625
Let me handle this.

20:13.458 --> 20:16.625
If you ever want to
see your kids again,

20:16.625 --> 20:19.500
meet me at Triple Dragon
in 20 minutes.

20:19.500 --> 20:21.041
And bring cash.

20:22.750 --> 20:25.375
Can you pass
the soy sauce, please?

20:25.375 --> 20:26.208
Eh.

20:28.000 --> 20:29.625
Heather!

20:29.625 --> 20:32.208
That thing you said
could happen is happening!

20:32.208 --> 20:39.125
♪
